<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-966-620  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 966 620.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  Dec 1989 v26 n12 p5(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>How networks survived the quake. (the San Francisco-areaearthquake of Oct 1989)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Harler, Curt.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Communications networks helped greatly during the 1989 SanFrancisco area earthquake.andP;  Apple Computer Inc's voice mailtelecommunications manager, David Hester, kept employees informedby updating his VMX voice mail systems many times each day.andP;  WhenCPC International in Pleasanton lost data communications with itsEnglewood Cliffs, NJ, offices, it restored services by using anintelligent dial backup system made by Control Resources Corp.andO;Pacific Bell kept its network up due to modern switchingequipment, reinforced floors and mechanical bracing of equipment,available auxiliary power sources, an extra 25 feet slack betweenjunction points in underground fiber optic cables andestablishment of an Emergency Operations Center which coordinatesall communications maintenance efforts.andP;  Pacific Bell's networkwas able to handle the 80 million phone calls on the day followingthe earthquake.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (communication systems)CPC International Inc. (communication systems)Control Resources Corp. (products)Pacific Bell (safety measures).andO;Ticker:    AAPL; CPC.andO;Topic:     EarthquakesNetwork ManagementNatural DisastersCommunications IndustrySan Francisco Bay Area Earthquake, 1989Voice MailTelecommunicationsCommunications EquipmentFiber Optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andO;Person:    Hester, David (management).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>